I choose this data because I love blackfriday and I love shopping, and I want to know did men or women spend more money on blackfriday and in which age spend more money.

library(readr)
BlackFriday <- read_csv("~/Downloads/BlackFriday.csv")
Parsed with column specification:
cols(
  User_ID = col_double(),
  Product_ID = col_character(),
  Gender = col_character(),
  Age = col_character(),
  Occupation = col_double(),
  City_Category = col_character(),
  Stay_In_Current_City_Years = col_character(),
  Marital_Status = col_double(),
  Product_Category_1 = col_double(),
  Product_Category_2 = col_double(),
  Product_Category_3 = col_double(),
  Purchase = col_double()
)

  1. First part is summarise the total number in different gender for different age and list the top 5 Second part is summarise the total number in different gender From this one, the interesting thing is men in age 26-35 spend more money than others.
BlackFriday%>%
  group_by(Gender,Age)%>%
  summarise(count=n())%>%
  arrange(desc(count))%>%
  head(5)

4.This graph shows that divide gender into different and summarise the purchase, then find the relationship between age and purchase. Men spend more money than women at all ages. The reason might be men paid for their wives, or maybe men would like to buy some expensive things.

library(ggplot2)
BlackFriday %>%
group_by(Age,Gender) %>%
summarise(total_purchase = sum(Purchase))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Age, y = total_purchase)) +
geom_col(aes(fill = Gender))

5.This graph shows the relationship between total purchase and city category

BlackFriday %>%
group_by(User_ID, City_Category) %>%
summarise(total_purchase = sum(Purchase)) %>%
ggplot(aes(x = total_purchase, group = City_Category)) + 
geom_histogram(aes(fill=City_Category,binwidth = 300000, center = 150000))
  1. This graph divided city category into martial status,gender and then shows the relationship between city category and total purchase in different marital status O is married, 1 is not married From the graph, there is no obvious difference bewteen married or not married in women.However for male, there is an obvious difference between married or not married in city B and C whcih means after male get married, they would like to buy more things.
BlackFriday %>%
group_by(City_Category, Marital_Status,Gender) %>%
summarise(total_purchase = sum(Purchase)) %>%
ggplot(aes(x = City_Category, y = total_purchase)) + 
 geom_col(aes(fill = Marital_Status))+facet_grid(~ Gender)

7.The graph divide occupation in different gender, and then shows the relationship bewteen occpution and total purchase in different gender. In the dataset, it did not say the different number for occpution means. However, from the graph we can see that male still pruchase more than women no matter the occupation is

BlackFriday %>%
group_by(Occupation,Gender) %>%
summarise(total_purchase = sum(Purchase))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Occupation, y = total_purchase)) +
geom_col(aes(fill = Gender))

8.This graph stay in current city years into gender, and then shows the relationship bewteen stay incurrent city years and totap purchase in different gender

BlackFriday %>%
group_by(Stay_In_Current_City_Years,Gender,Age,Product_Category_2) %>%
summarise(total_purchase = sum(Purchase))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Stay_In_Current_City_Years, y = total_purchase)) +
geom_col(aes(fill = Gender))+facet_wrap(Age~.)

  1. This graph divde product category 1 into age and gender, then shows the relationship between product category 1 and total purchase into different age and gender
BlackFriday %>%
group_by(Product_Category_1,Age,Gender) %>%
summarise(total_purchase = sum(Purchase))%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Product_Category_1, y = total_purchase)) +
geom_col(aes(fill = Age))+facet_grid(~Gender)
